<div class="col-list">
	<div class="list-v">
	<div class="crop"><a href="/opinion/opinion/2121091/thailand-tightens-information-law"><img src="https://static.bangkokpost.com/media/content/dcx/2021/05/25/3983103.jpg" alt="Thailand tightens information law" title="Thailand tightens information law"   srcset="https://static.bangkokpost.com/media/content/dcx/2021/05/25/3983103_197.jpg 500w,https://static.bangkokpost.com/media/content/dcx/2021/05/25/3983103_355.jpg 700w,https://static.bangkokpost.com/media/content/dcx/2021/05/25/3983103_371.jpg 350w"  ></a></div>		<div class="list-detail">
			<h3>
				<a href="/opinion/opinion/2121091/thailand-tightens-information-law" >Thailand tightens information law</a>
							</h3>
			<p>In September 1997 Thailand became the first country in Asean to enact a freedom of information law. The Official Information Act (OIA), as it is known here, became a new benchmark for a free society as well as its openness and transparency. For the first time, the public had the right to access information, especially that previously held by the government.			</p>
			<div class="f-icon">
				<span>25 May 2021 </span>
					<span class="ic-comment"><a href="/opinion/opinion/2121091/thailand-tightens-information-law?view_comment=1"><i class="icon-comment"></i> 28</a></span>								</div>
			<div class="box-reporter">
								<span class="img-profile">
					 <a href="/opinion/columnist/3003"><img src="https://static.bangkokpost.com/media/columnist/1565757944.jpg" title="Thailand tightens information law" alt="Thailand tightens information law"  srcset="https://static.bangkokpost.com/media/columnist/1565757944_50.jpg 350w,https://static.bangkokpost.com/media/columnist/1565757944_50.jpg 500w,https://static.bangkokpost.com/media/columnist/1565757944_50.jpg 700w"  ></a>
				</span>
								<span class="name"><a href="/opinion/columnist/3003" class="link-unterline">Kavi Chongkittavorn</a></span>
			</div>
		</div>
	</div>
</div>

<div class="col-list">
	<div class="list-v">
	<div class="crop"><a href="/opinion/opinion/2120999/sub-salvage-mission-brings-jakarta-beijing-closer"><img src="https://static.bangkokpost.com/media/content/dcx/2021/05/25/3983019.jpg" alt="Sub salvage mission brings Jakarta, Beijing closer" title="Sub salvage mission brings Jakarta, Beijing closer"   srcset="https://static.bangkokpost.com/media/content/dcx/2021/05/25/3983019_197.jpg 500w,https://static.bangkokpost.com/media/content/dcx/2021/05/25/3983019_355.jpg 700w,https://static.bangkokpost.com/media/content/dcx/2021/05/25/3983019_371.jpg 350w"  ></a></div>		<div class="list-detail">
			<h3>
				<a href="/opinion/opinion/2120999/sub-salvage-mission-brings-jakarta-beijing-closer" >Sub salvage mission brings Jakarta, Beijing closer</a>
							</h3>
			<p>Amid the uncertainties surrounding the Covid-19 pandemic, Indonesia was deeply saddened by the sinking of KRI Nanggala 402 last month. On April 21, the Indonesian Navy submarine sunk off the coast of Bali after losing contact shortly after it was authorised to begin its operation. All 53 crew perished in the incident.			</p>
			<div class="f-icon">
				<span>25 May 2021 </span>
					<span class="ic-comment"><a href="/opinion/opinion/2120999/sub-salvage-mission-brings-jakarta-beijing-closer?view_comment=1"><i class="icon-comment"></i> 1</a></span>								</div>
			<div class="box-reporter">
								<span class="name"><a href="//search.bangkokpost.com/search/result_advanced?category=news&columnistName=Aristyo+Rizka+Darmawan" class="link-unterline"></a></span>
			</div>
		</div>
	</div>
</div>
